share_info.desc: Grilled Cheese’s comment: The important thing about the complex ('complexis' = 'intertwined') numbers is their geometry. For thousands of years we've known the trig identities cos(α+β)=cos(α)cos(β)-sin(α)sin(β) and sin(α+β)=sin(α)cos(β)+sin(β)cos(α), thus tan(α+β)=sin(α+β)/cos(α+β)=tan(β)+tan(α)/(1-tan(α)tan(β)). If we take polynomials f=a+bX and g=c+dX and plot them in a plane they have angles from the horizontal axis of tan(α)=b/a and tan(β) = d/c. If we multiply f and g together we have ac+(ad+bc)X+bdX². If we swapped out X² for -1 then we'd have (ac-bd)+(ad+bc)X. Tan of the angle of fg is thus (ad+bc)/(ac-bd)=(d/c+b/a)/(1-bd/ac) = tan(β)+tan(α)/(1-tan(α)tan(β)). This tells us that the angle of fg is the angle of f plus the angle of g. IE whenever we multiply two complex numbers together, treating 'X²=-1', then the angles add (and also the absolute values multiply). This setup leads to complex analysis, e^iθ plotting out a circle, being able to use trigonometry to solve differential equations like a pendulum or the wave equation in electromagnetism, Fourier series, and much much more 😅
